node.text:
This American crocodile floats in ambush in the murky water of the Rio Tarcoles in Costa Rica. These formidable predators can grow to be 4 meters long (13 ft) and weigh up to 400 kilograms (800 lbs).
American crocodiles used to be found in large numbers throughout the mangrove forests in Southern Florida, but were hunted to near extinction in the early to mid 1900s. Today, their population is slowly coming back thanks to local conservation efforts. These animals prefer coastal and saline water, contrasting the habitat preference of American alligators, which prefer freshwater rivers and wetlands.
